{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/bone-soft-tissue-sarcoma-recognition-referral/background-information/presentation/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"a27bf635-6878-5608-8d61-f30c114978f7","slug":"presentation","fullItemName":"Presentation","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 95dc6419-733e-49de-affc-1d0b56d59a25 --><h2>How does it present?</h2><!-- end field 95dc6419-733e-49de-affc-1d0b56d59a25 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 63cc50b7-e9a6-4404-b70c-56b490a7e9c6 --><!-- begin field cb14fb0c-6d25-4861-9e02-db4d9031c65a --><ul><li><strong>Bone sarcoma:</strong><ul><li>Pain and loss of function of the affected limb are the main presenting symptoms of bone sarcoma.</li><li>X-ray may show abnormalities suggestive of the sarcoma.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Soft tissue sarcoma:</strong><ul><li>Soft tissue sarcomas occur in connective tissue, so can occur in many parts of the body.</li><li>Most cases present with a mass, which may be painless, and may become quite large.</li><li>The main method of diagnosis is by biopsy, which is performed in secondary care.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/bone-soft-tissue-sarcoma-recognition-referral/references/\">National Collaborating Centre for Cancer, 2015</a>]</p><!-- end field cb14fb0c-6d25-4861-9e02-db4d9031c65a --><!-- end item 63cc50b7-e9a6-4404-b70c-56b490a7e9c6 -->","topic":{"id":"e4747ecc-d17a-5e2c-bd0c-69fc109a74f5","topicId":"6f65762b-a612-4ce9-80e5-ee8cb24f6dde","topicName":"Bone and soft tissue sarcoma - recognition and referral","slug":"bone-soft-tissue-sarcoma-recognition-referral","lastRevised":"Last revised in August 2020","chapters":[{"id":"edf8fdb6-68e6-5dac-916a-206d3893e4b8","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"0b6c5a9d-30a1-51f3-b16c-afbf78f00757","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-top